WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.980
Oxford Bookworms. Stage 1. Scotland. By Steve Flinders. Read by

00:29.980 --> 00:29.980
Joan Walker. Published

00:44.140 --> 00:53.760
Chapter 1. A special country. There is nowhere like Scotland.

00:54.800 --> 00:58.980
Scotland is a country in a

00:58.980 --> 01:06.260
country. It is part of Great Britain, England, Scotland and

01:06.260 --> 01:09.840
Wales, and of the United Kingdom,

01:10.680 --> 01:19.840
England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. Scotland is in the

01:19.840 --> 01:22.060
far north west of Europe

01:22.860 --> 01:28.640
between the Atlantic Ocean and the North Sea. It is

01:28.640 --> 01:33.460
often cold and grey and it rains a lot in

01:33.460 --> 01:38.680
some parts of the country. But the people of Scotland

01:38.680 --> 01:42.840
love their country and many visitors

01:42.840 --> 01:49.220
to Scotland love it too. They love the beautiful hills

01:49.220 --> 02:12.820
and mountains of the north, the sea and the

02:12.820 --> 02:18.640
and Scottish people are special too, often warm and friendly.

02:20.840 --> 02:22.960
There are about five million

02:22.960 --> 02:29.760
people in Scotland. Most Scots live in the south, in

02:29.760 --> 02:34.060
or near the big cities of Edinburgh and Glasgow.

02:35.300 --> 02:39.700
Most of the north of the country is very empty,

02:40.680 --> 02:45.140
not many people live there. A Scottish person

02:45.140 --> 02:51.860
is also called a Scott, but you cannot talk about

02:51.860 --> 02:59.160
a Scotch person. Scotch means whiskey, a drink made

02:59.160 --> 03:06.720
in Scotland. Scottish people are British, because Scotland is part

03:06.720 --> 03:07.840
of Great Britain,

03:08.400 --> 03:14.320
but you must not call Scottish people English. The Scots

03:14.320 --> 03:17.220
and the English are different.

03:19.100 --> 03:26.840
These days everyone in Scotland speaks English, but at one

03:26.840 --> 03:30.300
time people in the north and west

03:30.300 --> 03:36.020
of Scotland did not speak English. They had a different

03:36.020 --> 03:40.740
language, a beautiful language called Gaelic.

03:41.620 --> 03:48.100
About 60,000 people, 1% of the people in

03:48.100 --> 03:55.100
Scotland speak Gaelic now, but many more want Gaelic in

03:55.100 --> 03:59.680
their lives because it is part of the story of

03:59.680 --> 04:05.940
Scotland. Scotland is not a very hot country.

04:06.660 --> 04:11.080
In the summer the days are long and it can

04:11.080 --> 04:16.640
be warm, but in the winter the days can be

04:16.640 --> 04:17.700
just seven

04:17.700 --> 04:25.720
hours long and it often rains. For many years Scotland

04:25.720 --> 04:31.340
was a poor country, but now things are

04:31.340 --> 04:37.680
better for most people. There is oil and gas in

04:37.680 --> 04:40.640
the sea between Scotland and Norway.

04:41.940 --> 04:48.240
Edinburgh is an important place for money and there are

04:48.240 --> 04:51.920
big banks there like the Royal Bank of

04:51.920 --> 04:59.960
Scotland. People in many countries drink Scotch whiskey and the

04:59.960 --> 05:02.520
whiskey business makes a lot

05:02.520 --> 05:09.860
of money for Scotland. Tourists visit this beautiful country and

05:09.860 --> 05:12.700
that brings money to Scotland too.

05:13.580 --> 05:20.640
Many people love living and working there and more than

05:20.640 --> 05:25.540
20 million visitors go to Scotland each year.

05:39.460 --> 05:51.920
Chapter 2 Scotland is the oldest country in the world.

05:52.880 --> 05:59.780
Why? Because the hills of the Northwest and the Hebridean

05:59.780 --> 06:05.900
Islands are more than 2,700 million years

06:05.900 --> 06:11.500
old. You can walk on some of the oldest rocks

06:11.500 --> 06:19.040
in the world there. People first lived there 9,000

06:19.040 --> 06:19.620
years

06:19.620 --> 06:25.800
ago. At Scarabre on the Orkney Islands in the far

06:25.800 --> 06:30.660
north of Scotland you can see the houses of early

06:30.660 --> 06:37.980
people from about 5,000 years ago. The houses at

06:37.980 --> 06:43.100
Nap of Hower also on the Orkneys are the oldest

06:43.260 --> 06:50.640
in Europe. The Romans went to Scotland but they did

06:50.640 --> 06:57.720
not stay there for long. Between AD 122 and 128

06:58.360 --> 07:06.760
they built Hadrian's Wall. It was 117 kilometres long and

07:06.760 --> 07:10.860
went from sea to sea across the most

07:10.860 --> 07:18.580
northern part of England. The Romans stayed in England for

07:18.580 --> 07:24.060
nearly 300 years until about AD 400

07:25.200 --> 07:31.120
and then they left and went back to Rome. Today

07:31.120 --> 07:35.680
you can visit Hadrian's Wall in the north of

07:35.680 --> 07:42.720
England and walk along parts of it. Who were the

07:42.720 --> 07:48.840
first Scots? The people north of Hadrian's Wall

07:49.160 --> 07:55.480
were called Picts by the Romans. We can still see

07:55.480 --> 07:59.680
some of their story in their pictures in stone

08:00.560 --> 08:07.420
but there were also Scotty from Ireland. The name Scotland

08:07.420 --> 08:13.820
comes from the Scotty. Vikings from Norway

08:14.280 --> 08:21.620
and some English people from the south. These different peoples

08:21.620 --> 08:25.820
came under one king in the 800s.

08:26.380 --> 08:32.180
The first king of all the Scots many people say

08:32.180 --> 08:41.360
was Kenneth MacAlpin. He was king from 843 to 858.

08:42.000 --> 08:49.400
But the most famous Scottish king of this early time

08:49.400 --> 09:11.340
is Macbeth. 1040 to 1057. He is famous

09:11.340 --> 09:16.220
but he was not worse than many other kings of

09:16.220 --> 09:20.620
those early days. There were many battles

09:20.980 --> 09:28.800
between England and Scotland. One important Scot was William Wallace,

09:30.060 --> 09:33.920
about 1270 to 1305.

09:34.880 --> 09:41.860
You can learn about him in the film Braveheart. Then

09:41.860 --> 09:47.160
in 1314 the Scottish king Robert the Bruce

09:47.670 --> 09:53.200
took his men to the battle of Banachban. After the

09:53.200 --> 09:57.300
battle 10,000 Englishmen were dead

09:57.650 --> 10:03.180
and Robert became one of the most important kings in

10:03.180 --> 10:04.560
the story of Scotland.

10:06.110 --> 10:13.200
Soon after Scotland was free and stayed free for nearly

10:13.200 --> 10:15.000
300 years.

10:17.120 --> 10:24.320
In 1542 a little girl called Mary became queen of

10:24.320 --> 10:30.320
Scotland. She was six days old and only the second

10:30.320 --> 10:33.460
woman to be queen of this country.

10:33.460 --> 10:40.680
Mary Queen of Scots became a tall and beautiful woman

10:40.680 --> 10:46.020
but some Scots did not want her to be queen.

10:47.040 --> 10:53.320
Mary went to England and asked Elizabeth the English Queen

10:53.320 --> 10:57.560
for help but she did not get it.

10:58.440 --> 11:05.080
She never returned to Scotland and died in England after

11:05.080 --> 11:12.740
19 years. You can read Mary's story in Mary Queen

11:12.740 --> 11:16.920
of Scots, Oxford bookworms stage one.

11:16.920 --> 11:25.380
Mary's son James Stewart became king of Scotland and then

11:25.380 --> 11:28.960
King James I of England too.

11:30.540 --> 11:36.880
In 1707 the two countries became Great Britain.

11:38.300 --> 11:45.240
In the 1700s Scotland was more like two countries than

11:45.240 --> 11:50.880
one. There were rich cities in the south but there

11:50.880 --> 11:55.560
were poor country people in the highlands, the hill country

11:55.560 --> 11:58.920
in the centre and the north of Scotland.

11:59.420 --> 12:05.820
At that time Edinburgh was one of the most important

12:05.820 --> 12:10.580
cities in Europe and many famous thinkers lived there.

12:11.900 --> 12:20.220
Then in the 1800s Glasgow became rich. People built big

12:20.220 --> 12:23.580
ships there and later trains.

12:23.580 --> 12:32.040
So the south of Scotland had busy cities with beautiful

12:32.040 --> 12:37.360
buildings, lots of work and money.

12:37.360 --> 12:49.040
In the highlands things were very different. After 1714 Great

12:49.040 --> 12:54.980
Britain had German kings from Hanover in North Germany.

12:55.980 --> 13:02.180
Many Scots in the highlands wanted a Scottish king, someone

13:02.180 --> 13:07.340
from the Stewart family like Mary and James, not a

13:07.340 --> 13:09.520
German king in London.

13:10.520 --> 13:17.680
They wanted Charles Stewart, Bonnie Prince Charlie, the grandson of

13:17.680 --> 13:23.100
the last Stewart king, James II of England and the

13:23.100 --> 13:24.500
7th of Scotland.

13:25.920 --> 13:33.940
Charles Stewart left France and came to Scotland. He wanted

13:33.940 --> 13:37.580
to be king of Scotland and England too.

13:38.520 --> 13:44.640
But Charles and his men lost the battle of Culloden

13:44.640 --> 13:52.140
near Inverness in 1746. Culloden was the last big battle

13:52.140 --> 13:53.640
in Great Britain.

13:55.520 --> 14:02.200
After the battle the British soldiers looked for Charles but

14:02.200 --> 14:04.620
he went into the hills.

14:05.540 --> 14:10.800
The people of the highlands and the islands helped him

14:10.800 --> 14:16.460
to go back to France but life became difficult for

14:16.460 --> 14:17.780
them after that.

14:18.230 --> 14:24.480
The British soldiers stayed in the highlands and took away

14:24.480 --> 14:29.540
houses and land from the friends of Charles Stewart.

14:30.540 --> 14:37.580
After this many poor families left the highlands and went

14:37.580 --> 14:42.620
to the cities in the south of Scotland or to

14:42.620 --> 14:50.780
other countries, the USA, Canada, Australia and New Zealand.

14:51.780 --> 14:57.860
Some went because they wanted to begin a new life

14:57.860 --> 15:03.560
but others went because the rich owners of the land

15:03.560 --> 15:07.420
in Scotland wanted to put animals there.

15:08.420 --> 15:17.800
Between 1840 and 1880 40,000 people left just one

15:17.800 --> 15:20.780
island, the island of Sky.

15:22.360 --> 15:29.280
Life became more difficult in the 1900s but oil and

15:29.280 --> 15:33.480
gas in the North Sea began to bring money to

15:33.480 --> 15:36.500
Scotland again in the 1970s.

15:37.640 --> 15:42.560
Let's look now at some of the famous places in

15:42.560 --> 15:44.180
the Scotland of today.

15:57.940 --> 16:01.440
Chapter 3 Edinburgh

16:03.780 --> 16:10.260
Many people begin a visit to Scotland in Edinburgh, the

16:10.260 --> 16:11.780
capital city.

16:11.780 --> 16:18.980
Edinburgh is an old city with many important and interesting

16:18.980 --> 16:26.040
buildings and about 470,000 people live there.

16:27.240 --> 16:33.700
After London, Edinburgh is the second city for visitors in

16:33.700 --> 16:33.960
Britain.

16:35.280 --> 16:40.260
Come to Edinburgh by train from the south and you

16:40.260 --> 16:42.500
arrive at Waverly station.

16:43.820 --> 16:49.160
When you come out of the station, Edinburgh Castle is

16:49.160 --> 16:52.560
in front of you, high up on a hill.

16:53.640 --> 16:59.440
From the castle, you can see all over the city.

17:00.340 --> 17:05.160
You can see the famous one o'clock gum and

17:05.160 --> 17:10.160
at one o'clock from Monday to Saturday, you can

17:10.160 --> 17:11.420
hear it too.

17:11.420 --> 17:18.680
It makes a very big noise. Edinburgh is built on

17:18.680 --> 17:23.420
hills but you can walk around the city easily.

17:24.820 --> 17:29.740
From the castle, you can go down the royal mile

17:29.740 --> 17:31.660
to Holy Roode house.

17:32.660 --> 17:38.920
This building, 300 years old, is the home of Queen

17:38.920 --> 17:42.420
Elizabeth II when she comes to Edinburgh.

17:43.680 --> 17:48.480
This part of the city is called the Old Town.

17:49.800 --> 17:56.880
Then take a walk along Princess Street in the New

17:56.880 --> 17:57.320
Town.

17:58.320 --> 18:06.280
The New Town, 1767 to 1840, is more than 150

18:06.280 --> 18:10.780
years old now but still has this name.

18:12.160 --> 18:17.320
Some shops have the famous Scottish tartans.

18:18.140 --> 18:22.920
Each clan, a big old Scottish family, is called the

18:22.920 --> 18:25.700
clan, has its own tartan.

18:26.480 --> 18:30.440
And in the windows, you can see the different tartans

18:30.440 --> 18:32.560
for famous Scottish clans.

18:33.860 --> 18:39.560
People with a Scottish family name can buy and wear

18:39.560 --> 18:41.520
the family tartan.

18:42.300 --> 18:46.420
People without a Scottish name can buy and wear a

18:46.420 --> 18:47.160
tartan too.

18:49.540 --> 18:52.980
Edinburgh has many wonderful things.

18:54.100 --> 18:58.720
The buildings in the New Town in Charlotte Square, for

18:58.720 --> 19:00.820
example, are very beautiful.

19:01.760 --> 19:04.400
There are very good museums.

19:05.400 --> 19:10.480
The National Museum of Scotland is near the royal mile

19:10.480 --> 19:15.720
and tells you a lot about the Scotland of yesterday

19:15.720 --> 19:17.660
and today.

19:19.320 --> 19:25.440
The National Gallery of Scotland, near the castle, has beautiful

19:25.440 --> 19:31.060
pictures from Scotland and from many other countries too.

19:32.060 --> 19:38.740
In August, thousands of people come to the Edinburgh Festival.

19:39.780 --> 19:46.980
Singing, dancing, cinema, books, pictures, theatre.

19:48.000 --> 19:53.860
You can see and do hundreds of different things at

19:53.860 --> 19:54.500
the festival.

19:55.500 --> 20:02.840
And also in August, every evening for three weeks, you

20:02.840 --> 20:08.400
can go to the Edinburgh Military Tattoo at Edinburgh Castle.

20:09.360 --> 20:15.100
There, you can see soldiers and hear music from Scotland

20:15.100 --> 20:17.900
and from lots of other countries.

20:19.700 --> 20:25.780
On the 31st of December, everyone wants to be in

20:25.780 --> 20:30.960
the city centre for the famous Street Party for Hognonay.

20:31.680 --> 20:35.780
That is the Scottish name for New Year's Eve.

20:36.900 --> 20:42.680
But there are only 100,000 tickets and they go

20:42.680 --> 20:43.880
very quickly.

20:43.880 --> 20:50.540
The party begins in one year and finishes in the

20:50.540 --> 20:53.540
next. That is a good time.

21:20.720 --> 21:23.520
Chapter 4

21:26.300 --> 21:34.520
About 630,000 people live in the city and about

21:34.520 --> 21:39.600
1.2 million in and near it.

21:40.660 --> 21:46.480
It is not very far from Edinburgh, about 50 minutes

21:46.480 --> 21:51.080
by train, but it is very different.

21:51.900 --> 21:58.420
The river Clyde runs through the centre of Glasgow and

21:58.420 --> 22:02.720
it has an important part in the story of Glasgow.

22:04.480 --> 22:10.200
200 years ago, Glasgow was a small town.

22:11.640 --> 22:16.960
Then British ships began to go all over the world.

22:17.920 --> 22:22.020
Big ships came up and down the river Clyde.

22:22.780 --> 22:25.940
They carried things from other countries.

22:27.500 --> 22:33.320
In the 1800s, Britain was the richest country in the

22:33.320 --> 22:33.700
world.

22:34.700 --> 22:42.980
Shipbuilding became very important and Glasgow became a city of

22:42.980 --> 22:43.780
shipbuilders.

22:44.960 --> 22:50.440
At one time, it was the fourth largest city in

22:50.440 --> 22:55.480
Europe after London, Paris and Berlin.

22:56.480 --> 23:02.040
You can see some of the beautiful buildings from that

23:02.040 --> 23:04.220
time in George Square.

23:05.360 --> 23:11.200
Today, there is not much shipbuilding. Some parts of Glasgow

23:11.200 --> 23:16.440
are very poor and many people have no work.

23:17.380 --> 23:23.720
But things are changing in Glasgow. Ask a glass region,

23:24.300 --> 23:26.100
a person from Glasgow.

23:27.280 --> 23:33.920
To them, Glasgow is the friendliest city in Britain and

23:33.920 --> 23:38.280
one of the most exciting cities in Britain too.

23:39.280 --> 23:43.240
There are lots of things to do at night in

23:43.240 --> 23:43.480
Glasgow.

23:44.800 --> 23:50.060
It is perhaps the best city in Britain after London

23:50.060 --> 23:51.720
for shopping too.

23:52.880 --> 23:58.860
Like Edinburgh, it is a green city. It has 70

23:58.860 --> 24:04.140
parks and you can often see the hills from the

24:04.140 --> 24:05.720
centre of the city.

24:06.860 --> 24:13.060
It is a city of museums. You can see many

24:13.060 --> 24:18.880
beautiful pictures in the Glasgow City Museum and Art Gallery

24:19.640 --> 24:24.660
and in the Borough Collection and Pollock House, south of

24:24.660 --> 24:25.020
the Clyde.

24:26.300 --> 24:30.660
It is the city of Charles Renney Mackintosh.

24:31.680 --> 24:38.840
About 100 years ago, Mackintosh and three friends began a

24:38.840 --> 24:43.180
new look in building, Art Nouveau.

24:44.140 --> 24:47.940
Much of Mackintosh's best work is in Glasgow.

24:48.940 --> 24:53.760
His Glasgow School of Art is on Renfrew Street.

24:55.060 --> 24:59.380
After you visit it, you can have a coffee at

24:59.380 --> 25:04.840
the Willow Tea Rooms, also by Mackintosh, on Socki Hall

25:04.840 --> 25:05.320
Street.

25:06.540 --> 25:11.720
And Glasgow is, of course, a big football city.

25:12.260 --> 25:18.940
You can watch Glasgow Celtic at Celtic Park or Glasgow

25:18.940 --> 25:21.920
Rangers at the Ibrox Stadium

25:21.920 --> 25:25.740
on Saturdays between August and May.

25:39.440 --> 25:45.940
Chapter 5. Four Scottish Cities

25:47.740 --> 25:56.380
Aberdeen, with 192,000 people, is the third biggest city

25:56.380 --> 25:57.440
in Scotland.

25:58.460 --> 26:02.640
It is in the east of the country, on the

26:02.640 --> 26:08.400
north sea, and it is between two rivers, the D

26:08.400 --> 26:10.640
and the Don.

26:11.640 --> 26:20.260
Fishing and shipbuilding were once important here, but now it

26:20.260 --> 26:24.760
is famous as the oil capital of the UK.

26:26.120 --> 26:32.100
Boats and planes leave Aberdeen every day for the oil

26:32.100 --> 26:35.500
and gas fields of the north sea.

26:35.980 --> 26:43.480
It has two universities and many wonderful parks and gardens.

26:44.540 --> 26:51.240
The musicians, Annie Lennox and Evelyn Glenny, both come from

26:51.240 --> 26:51.600
Aberdeen.

26:53.440 --> 26:59.760
Visitors to Aberdeen often go to its beautiful long beach

26:59.760 --> 27:03.620
or go climbing south of the city.

27:04.620 --> 27:11.320
Aberdeen is close to the cold and beautiful mountains called

27:11.320 --> 27:18.740
the Cangorms, and there are more than 350 castles in

27:18.740 --> 27:20.080
this part of the country.

27:21.360 --> 27:26.160
One of them is Balmoral, the Queen's Castle.

27:27.620 --> 27:31.360
Queen Elizabeth comes here every summer.

27:33.200 --> 27:38.440
Dundee, on the river Tay, is near the north sea

27:38.440 --> 27:38.820
too.

27:40.060 --> 27:45.880
Like Glasgow and Aberdeen, it was once important for shipbuilding.

27:46.860 --> 27:52.660
The ship Discovery was built here and left Dundee in

27:52.660 --> 27:55.340
1901 for Antarctica.

27:56.340 --> 28:01.660
Now, more than a hundred years later, the ship is

28:01.660 --> 28:06.180
back in Dundee again and you can visit it there.

28:07.540 --> 28:12.700
Dundee is also famous for Marmalade.

28:13.660 --> 28:21.440
The Kila family began making orange marmalade here in 1797

28:21.440 --> 28:27.840
and it became famous all over the world.

28:28.340 --> 28:33.780
Inverness is the only city in the Highlands.

28:34.780 --> 28:40.020
The best bagpipers in the world come here to play

28:40.020 --> 28:41.480
every September.

28:42.860 --> 28:47.520
It is close to the beautiful lake called Loch Ness.

28:48.540 --> 28:51.580
Loch is the Gaelic word for lake.

28:52.410 --> 28:59.040
A very big animal called the Loch Ness Monster, or

28:59.040 --> 29:02.740
Nessie, lives in Loch Ness.

29:04.100 --> 29:09.740
An old story says this and thousands of tourists go

29:09.740 --> 29:15.520
there every year to look for it, but Nessie does

29:15.520 --> 29:16.160
not come.

29:16.800 --> 29:20.220
Perhaps this is just a story for tourists.

29:22.000 --> 29:28.020
Then there is Stirling to the northeast of Glasgow.

29:29.680 --> 29:34.700
Many visitors go through Stirling when they go to the

29:34.700 --> 29:35.080
Highlands.

29:36.080 --> 29:41.700
It has a wonderful castle, one of the biggest and

29:41.700 --> 29:44.580
most important castles in Scotland.

29:45.720 --> 29:53.080
The Battle of Bannekburne in 1314 was near here and

29:53.080 --> 29:58.820
here Mary became Queen of Scotland when she was only

29:58.820 --> 30:00.760
six days old.

30:16.100 --> 30:35.060
Chapter 6. Highlands and Islands

30:35.060 --> 30:39.420
There are not a lot of people here, only eight

30:39.420 --> 30:44.880
people per square kilometre, but there is a lot of

30:44.880 --> 30:50.460
beautiful country with locks, rivers and hills.

30:51.460 --> 30:57.460
The Highlands have two of the most wonderful train journeys

30:57.460 --> 31:04.200
in the world, from Inverness to Kyle of Lachauch and

31:04.200 --> 31:06.380
from Fort William to Mallag.

31:06.980 --> 31:13.600
All visitors can go by road past the beautiful Loch

31:13.600 --> 31:16.960
Lomond to the mountains at Glencoe.

31:18.720 --> 31:23.620
Do you love to be out of the cities, walking,

31:24.300 --> 31:29.920
climbing, looking for birds and animals or taking photos?

31:31.460 --> 31:33.900
Then the Highlands are for you.

31:34.900 --> 31:38.380
The mountains are not very high.

31:39.520 --> 31:46.180
Ben Nevis, the highest in the UK, is 1,344

31:46.180 --> 31:51.100
metres, but they can be difficult.

31:52.320 --> 31:59.120
Sometimes cold weather comes from the north, so walkers and

31:59.120 --> 32:02.780
climbers need to be careful in the winter.

32:02.780 --> 32:05.420
And in the summer too.

32:06.680 --> 32:10.200
What can you see in the Highlands?

32:11.380 --> 32:17.400
There are not many trees on the hills, but there

32:17.400 --> 32:19.420
is beautiful heaven.

32:20.880 --> 32:25.700
The water in the locks is cold and dark.

32:26.840 --> 32:33.060
Red deer run across the hills, and perhaps you can

32:33.060 --> 32:36.520
see golden eagles high up in the sky.

32:37.900 --> 32:42.860
When you leave the road, you are soon in empty

32:42.860 --> 32:43.460
country.

32:44.540 --> 32:50.360
There is nothing but the hills and the sky, the

32:50.360 --> 32:52.480
birds and the animals.

32:55.940 --> 33:04.280
Islands Scotland has hundreds of islands, and life is different

33:04.280 --> 33:04.700
there.

33:05.980 --> 33:08.600
The island towns are small.

33:09.800 --> 33:14.840
On some islands, like sky and the islands of the

33:14.840 --> 33:19.380
Hebrides, many of the people speak Gaelic.

33:20.380 --> 33:26.620
On the islands of Lewis and Harris, some people do

33:26.620 --> 33:32.300
not work, drive or watch TV on Sundays.

33:33.360 --> 33:40.000
In the north, the islands of Orkney and Shetland are

33:40.000 --> 33:42.800
nearer to Norway than to London.

33:44.340 --> 33:49.860
From open, in the west of Scotland, you can go

33:49.860 --> 33:52.820
to some of the islands in the inner Hebrides.

33:53.800 --> 33:59.120
Here, you can see sea animals, like seals.

34:00.580 --> 34:05.260
From mull, you can go to see the beautiful caves

34:05.260 --> 34:09.520
of Stapha, or you can visit Iona.

34:10.940 --> 34:16.440
St Colombo came to the small island of Iona from

34:16.440 --> 34:23.820
Ireland in 563, and began to teach people about Christianity.

34:25.400 --> 34:32.040
Today, Iona is an important Christian centre, and half a

34:32.040 --> 34:35.400
million people go there every year.

34:36.060 --> 34:42.240
The bodies of Kenneth MacAlpin and other Scottish kings are

34:42.240 --> 34:43.860
here on Iona.

34:45.280 --> 34:51.200
You can also go to Sky, perhaps the most famous

34:51.200 --> 34:55.700
and the most beautiful of the islands of Scotland,

34:56.460 --> 35:01.520
and see the dark mountains called the Kulin near the

35:01.520 --> 35:01.720
sea.

35:03.440 --> 35:09.100
From other pool, you can go across to Lewis in

35:09.100 --> 35:10.200
the outer Hebrides.

35:10.940 --> 35:17.420
There are long, white, empty beaches here, and the 5

35:17.420 --> 35:21.300
,000-year-old stone circle at Kalanish.

35:22.140 --> 35:26.980
There are 50 standing stones at Kalanish.

35:27.900 --> 35:32.840
Time goes more slowly in this quiet, special place.

35:48.120 --> 35:50.220
Chapter 7

35:50.840 --> 35:54.560
Sport and Free Time

35:55.980 --> 36:03.960
Many Scottish people love sport, and in Scotland, many people

36:03.960 --> 36:09.360
play golf, the rich and the not-so rich.

36:10.720 --> 36:16.680
Golf began in this country, and the golf capital of

36:16.680 --> 36:24.220
Scotland is St Andrews, a small university city near Edinburgh.

36:24.900 --> 36:31.840
There are more than 400 golf courses in Scotland, and

36:31.840 --> 36:34.380
many of them are very beautiful.

36:35.820 --> 36:41.320
In the summer, when the days are long, you can

36:41.320 --> 36:46.160
play from 7 in the morning to 10 at night.

36:47.580 --> 36:51.720
Football is also very important.

36:53.180 --> 37:00.020
In 2006, Scotland had the 10th highest number of football

37:00.020 --> 37:03.580
clubs of any country in the world.

37:04.680 --> 37:10.700
Celtic and Rangers are the biggest and the most famous

37:10.700 --> 37:11.840
Scottish clubs,

37:11.840 --> 37:19.040
but others, like Aberdeen, also do well in Scotland and

37:19.040 --> 37:20.020
in Europe.

37:21.460 --> 37:26.680
The Scots play rugby football too, and it is an

37:26.680 --> 37:28.680
important sport in Scotland.

37:28.680 --> 37:39.960
In 1990, Scotland beat England, Wales, Ireland and France at

37:39.960 --> 37:45.620
rugby, and every year the Scots want to do this

37:45.620 --> 37:46.220
again.

37:47.220 --> 37:53.580
But now Italy plays too, so they need to beat

37:53.580 --> 37:56.560
five countries, not four.

37:58.560 --> 38:05.760
Scotland's hills and mountains are good for sports too, walking,

38:06.300 --> 38:09.640
climbing, cycling and more.

38:10.640 --> 38:16.820
And there are lots of exciting sports on, in and

38:16.820 --> 38:23.000
under the water, in the locks, rivers and the sea.

38:24.460 --> 38:29.220
You can take a kayak down a fast river, for

38:29.220 --> 38:32.340
example, or out to sea.

38:33.340 --> 38:37.860
The rain does not matter when you do these sports.

38:39.460 --> 38:45.440
Between May and September, in more than a hundred different

38:45.440 --> 38:51.020
places in Scotland, people meet at a Highland Games,

38:52.300 --> 38:55.800
a festival of Scottish sports and music.

38:56.800 --> 39:03.700
You can see big men tossing the camber, listen to

39:03.700 --> 39:08.880
Scottish music on the back pipes and watch Scottish dancing.

39:10.460 --> 39:17.020
Not all Scots men have kilts, but more and more

39:17.020 --> 39:22.160
of them wear one sometimes, and lots of people wear

39:22.160 --> 39:23.760
kilts to the games.

39:24.760 --> 39:30.880
When a Scotsman wears a kilt, he is saying, I

39:30.880 --> 39:32.240
like being Scottish.

39:33.520 --> 39:39.060
A kilt needs about six metres of tartan.

39:40.100 --> 39:46.260
When one of the big clans, like Clan Donald, Mackenzie

39:46.260 --> 39:52.700
or Stuart has a big meeting, people come from many

39:52.700 --> 39:53.320
countries.

39:54.880 --> 39:58.860
Many of them wear kilts in the clan tartan when

39:58.860 --> 39:59.380
they come.

40:00.380 --> 40:07.060
One clan in the USA, Clan Donald, has 4,000

40:07.060 --> 40:07.540
families.

40:08.580 --> 40:15.420
Their families went from Scotland to the USA, perhaps 150

40:15.420 --> 40:20.620
years ago, but they still want to be Scottish.

40:34.740 --> 40:36.560
Chapter 8

40:37.380 --> 40:40.420
5. Great Scots

40:41.940 --> 40:48.900
Scotland is not a big country and does not have

40:48.900 --> 40:55.300
many people, but there are many famous and important Scots.

40:55.300 --> 40:58.580
Here are five of them.

41:00.420 --> 41:09.260
Robert Adam, 1728-1792, made some of the best buildings

41:09.260 --> 41:14.740
in Great Britain in the second half of the 1700s.

41:15.740 --> 41:21.560
He went to school and university in Edinburgh, and then

41:21.560 --> 41:26.680
to Rome for five years to learn about the buildings

41:26.680 --> 41:27.140
there.

41:28.260 --> 41:31.240
Then he came back to Britain.

41:32.500 --> 41:37.900
He worked on the new town in Edinburgh, and you

41:37.900 --> 41:41.920
can see buildings by him in Charlotte Square.

41:41.920 --> 41:48.960
There are many beautiful buildings by Adam in England and

41:48.960 --> 41:49.400
Scotland.

41:50.520 --> 41:56.580
People come from all over Europe and America to look

41:56.580 --> 41:56.940
at them.

41:59.520 --> 42:09.600
David Hume, 1711-1776, was a great thinker and writer.

42:10.760 --> 42:16.200
People still read and talk about his books today because

42:16.200 --> 42:18.320
they are so important.

42:18.880 --> 42:25.380
He also wrote a very long history of England, at

42:25.380 --> 42:29.740
that time the most important book of this kind.

42:31.140 --> 42:36.320
Hume went to the University of Edinburgh when he was

42:36.320 --> 42:38.100
12 years old.

42:38.920 --> 42:45.060
Later he went to France and made friends with famous

42:45.060 --> 42:50.020
French thinkers like Voltaire and Rousseau.

42:50.880 --> 42:57.140
His most important book is A Treatise of Human Nature,

42:57.920 --> 43:01.140
1739-1740.

43:02.140 --> 43:12.460
The next great Scott is Robert Burns, 1759-1796.

43:13.660 --> 43:19.580
The Scots call him Robbie or Robbie Burns.

43:20.580 --> 43:26.760
He was born into a poor country family, the oldest

43:26.760 --> 43:32.440
of seven children near air in southwest Scotland.

43:33.460 --> 43:38.780
He began writing poems when he was still a boy.

43:39.740 --> 43:47.540
He wrote about important things, about life and love, rich

43:47.540 --> 43:51.560
people and poor people and Scotland.

43:52.780 --> 43:58.440
His words still speak to us today and many Scots

43:58.440 --> 44:00.560
love his poems.

44:01.680 --> 44:08.120
Burns was born on the 25th of January and that

44:08.120 --> 44:12.620
night is called Burns Night by the Scots.

44:14.080 --> 44:19.700
On Burns Night there are special dinners, not just in

44:19.700 --> 44:24.620
Scotland but for Scottish people in other countries too.

44:25.580 --> 44:32.980
They eat haggis, a special Scottish food, drink whiskey and

44:32.980 --> 44:35.380
say poems by Burns.

44:37.140 --> 44:42.360
And at midnight on the 31st of December in many

44:42.360 --> 44:49.260
English-speaking countries, people sing the words of Burns when

44:49.260 --> 44:49.860
they sing,

44:49.860 --> 44:52.180
Old Lang Zion.

44:53.440 --> 44:59.960
The name of the song means something like long, long

44:59.960 --> 45:00.660
ago.

45:03.300 --> 45:11.880
James Watt, 1736-1819 was born in Greenock near Glasgow

45:11.880 --> 45:16.640
and did not often go to school when he was

45:16.640 --> 45:17.120
a child.

45:17.780 --> 45:23.020
He stayed at home and his mother was his teacher.

45:23.860 --> 45:30.240
Watt was a quick thinker and he liked to build

45:30.240 --> 45:32.080
things with his hands.

45:33.520 --> 45:38.360
He got work building things for the teachers at the

45:38.360 --> 45:39.920
University of Glasgow.

45:40.820 --> 45:45.600
There he became interested in steam engines.

45:46.960 --> 45:53.100
He began a business with his friend Matthew Bolton and

45:53.100 --> 46:05.720
from 1794 to 1824 they made 1,164 steam engines.

46:06.720 --> 46:12.480
These engines changed Great Britain and the world.

46:13.500 --> 46:18.660
After what? The world was a different place.

46:21.360 --> 46:30.440
Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, 1859-1930 was born in Edinburgh,

46:31.000 --> 46:33.560
went to the University of Edinburgh

46:34.320 --> 46:36.420
and became a doctor.

46:37.840 --> 46:42.220
But he did not make much money as a doctor.

46:43.140 --> 46:49.500
So he began to write stories about a detective called

46:49.500 --> 46:51.200
Sherlock Holmes.

46:52.440 --> 47:00.020
Soon Sherlock Holmes was famous and Conan Doyle became rich

47:00.020 --> 47:01.520
and famous too.

47:02.410 --> 47:08.860
He wrote many stories about Holmes and his friend Doctor

47:08.860 --> 47:15.820
Watson and also wrote stories about a man called Professor

47:15.820 --> 47:16.580
Challenger.

47:18.280 --> 47:24.160
There are films of many Sherlock Holmes stories and you

47:24.160 --> 47:27.460
can read some of them in bookworms.

47:28.390 --> 47:34.340
Sherlock Holmes and the Duke's son and Sherlock Holmes and

47:34.340 --> 47:35.620
the Sport of Kings.

47:36.920 --> 47:39.420
Oxford bookworms stage 1.

47:41.070 --> 47:43.400
Do you know any other great Scots?

47:58.000 --> 48:05.580
Chapter 9. Food and Drink. Food.

48:07.020 --> 48:13.380
In the earliest days Scottish people took their food from

48:13.380 --> 48:17.060
the sea, the rivers and the land.

48:18.060 --> 48:23.260
From the sea and the rivers came fish.

48:24.440 --> 48:31.140
And from the land they got fruit, vegetables and meat.

48:32.360 --> 48:36.880
And they got oats from the land too.

48:37.880 --> 48:44.680
They made their bread from oats and they made porridge

48:44.680 --> 48:49.280
from oats and water for a hot breakfast.

48:50.700 --> 48:56.720
People still eat all of these things in Scotland today,

48:57.400 --> 49:00.040
but they eat new things too.

49:01.040 --> 49:08.040
From 1900 on many people began to come to Scotland

49:08.040 --> 49:12.560
from countries like Italy and India

49:12.560 --> 49:17.160
and they brought different food with them.

49:18.300 --> 49:23.120
There is a lot of good food in Scotland.

49:24.040 --> 49:29.720
It is famous for its fish like salmon and haddock

49:29.720 --> 49:33.040
and for other food from the sea.

49:34.660 --> 49:39.100
Fish farming is very important for Scotland.

49:39.980 --> 49:45.900
It gives work to about 6,000 people and brings

49:45.900 --> 49:48.700
lots of money into the country.

49:49.700 --> 49:55.640
Then there is Scottish beef, the best beef in the

49:55.640 --> 49:57.420
world the Scots say.

49:58.440 --> 50:04.240
And haggis made from meat, oats and other things.

50:05.540 --> 50:10.000
Scottish raspberries are also very good.

50:10.580 --> 50:16.260
The Scots like to make a dish called kranakim with

50:16.260 --> 50:19.900
raspberries, oats and whiskey.

50:21.260 --> 50:25.120
People with lots of money can go to a hotel

50:25.120 --> 50:28.020
like Glen Eagles near Perth.

50:28.860 --> 50:33.280
Perhaps the most famous hotel in Scotland today.

50:33.280 --> 50:42.700
It has 232 bedrooms, 3 golf courses and some of

50:42.700 --> 50:44.740
the best Scottish food.

50:45.800 --> 50:50.800
But good food is not a part of life for

50:50.800 --> 50:57.420
everybody in Scotland and some poorer Scots do not eat

50:57.420 --> 50:58.260
very well.

50:59.210 --> 51:06.880
British men usually live to 77 years old but in

51:06.880 --> 51:12.520
some parts of Glasgow they only live to 54.

51:14.140 --> 51:20.960
Better food is very important for Scottish people today and

51:20.960 --> 51:21.360
tomorrow.

51:23.880 --> 51:24.880
Drink.

51:26.660 --> 51:31.260
The word whiskey comes from the Gaelic, whiskey by the

51:31.260 --> 51:32.860
water of life.

51:34.520 --> 51:39.980
Whiskey also called Scotch is made in a distillery.

51:41.160 --> 51:46.220
There are more than 100 distilleries in Scotland.

51:47.060 --> 51:51.300
Some near Edinburgh and Glasgow in the south.

51:52.080 --> 51:57.240
One on the island of Sky and three on the

51:57.240 --> 51:58.880
Orkneys in the north.

52:00.120 --> 52:04.360
There are nine on the small island of Isla.

52:05.360 --> 52:09.640
About half of the distilleries are near the river Spain,

52:10.280 --> 52:11.560
east of Inverness.

52:12.780 --> 52:18.180
Many visitors like to visit the distilleries there and try

52:18.180 --> 52:19.620
the different whiskeys.

52:21.120 --> 52:27.040
Visitors to Edinburgh can visit the Scotch Whiskey Heritage Centre

52:27.040 --> 52:28.660
near the castle.

52:30.840 --> 52:36.500
Whiskey is good but another drink in Scotland is better.

52:37.340 --> 52:38.300
Water.

52:39.520 --> 52:44.900
The whiskey is good because the water from the hills

52:44.900 --> 52:46.120
is good.

52:47.080 --> 52:51.860
On a hot day a drink of Scottish hill water

52:51.860 --> 52:55.820
can be the best drink in the world.

53:09.920 --> 53:12.040
Chapter 10

53:12.820 --> 53:16.280
Scotland and the World

53:17.280 --> 53:22.300
Scotland is a small country.

53:23.740 --> 53:27.540
Only five million people live there.

53:28.520 --> 53:35.660
But for millions more across the world Scotland is very

53:35.660 --> 53:36.460
important.

53:37.800 --> 53:39.560
Why is this?

53:40.560 --> 53:49.200
In the 1800s many people left Scotland and went to

53:49.200 --> 53:50.060
other countries.

53:51.260 --> 53:58.440
People in the Highlands left their homes and villages because

53:58.440 --> 54:02.140
they were very poor and hungry.

54:03.420 --> 54:09.200
Sometimes the rich people there wanted them to leave.

54:10.460 --> 54:17.020
Many others from the south of Scotland left because they

54:17.020 --> 54:21.840
wanted a better life in a new country.

54:23.440 --> 54:32.680
Between the 1820s and 1914 more than two million people

54:32.680 --> 54:35.940
went from Scotland across the

54:35.940 --> 54:43.800
seas to the United States, Canada, Australia and New Zealand.

54:44.800 --> 54:48.300
More went in the 1920s.

54:49.040 --> 54:55.340
Today there are six million Scottish Americans in the USA.

54:56.700 --> 55:02.380
Every year many people walk through New York on the

55:02.380 --> 55:05.060
6th of April, tartan day.

55:06.020 --> 55:11.540
A lot of Scottish Americans go back to Scotland as

55:11.540 --> 55:11.800
tourists.

55:12.900 --> 55:19.140
They want to find their past and to understand it.

55:20.940 --> 55:26.980
So Scotland is important in the story of other countries

55:26.980 --> 55:27.540
too.

55:28.540 --> 55:35.520
Two great Scots in the USA are Alexander Graham Bell

55:35.520 --> 55:47.400
1847-1922 and Andrew Carnegie 1837-1919.

55:48.400 --> 55:51.900
Bell made the first telephone.

55:53.180 --> 56:00.460
He began the Bell Telephone Company in 1877 and by

56:00.460 --> 56:07.960
1885 more than 150,000 people in the

56:07.960 --> 56:10.340
USA had telephones.

56:11.340 --> 56:18.840
In 1915 he made the first telephone call across the

56:18.840 --> 56:23.340
United States from New York to San Francisco.

56:25.120 --> 56:29.460
After he died in Canada at the age of 75

56:29.460 --> 56:34.560
all the telephones in North America were quiet

56:34.560 --> 56:38.020
for one minute to remember him.

56:40.400 --> 56:46.860
Andrew Carnegie's family left Scotland when he was 11 and

56:46.860 --> 56:47.960
went to the USA.

56:49.580 --> 56:56.500
Carnegie worked hard and by the 1880s he had many

56:56.500 --> 57:00.860
businesses and was very rich, the richest

57:00.860 --> 57:03.300
man in the world.

57:04.760 --> 57:10.200
When he stopped working he gave his money to other

57:10.200 --> 57:10.640
people.

57:12.020 --> 57:19.660
Carnegie's money built schools, universities and other buildings in the

57:19.660 --> 57:21.680
USA, the UK,

57:22.660 --> 57:26.620
Australia, New Zealand and Ireland.

57:27.620 --> 57:34.860
Today his money still helps millions of people around the

57:34.860 --> 57:36.660
world every year.

57:38.620 --> 57:44.440
Many Scots love to visit other countries and do new

57:44.440 --> 57:45.320
things.

57:46.320 --> 57:55.600
David Livingston 1813-1873 went to Africa to begin schools

57:55.600 --> 57:59.960
and to tell Africans about

57:59.960 --> 58:01.160
Christianity.

58:02.260 --> 58:08.740
He was the first European to see the Victoria Falls

58:08.740 --> 58:12.380
between Zambia and Zimbabwe.

58:13.380 --> 58:18.940
And the first to go across Africa from the Atlantic

58:18.940 --> 58:23.480
in the West to the Indian Ocean in

58:23.480 --> 58:24.120
the East.

58:26.250 --> 58:32.120
Alan Bean born 1932 is a Scottish American.

58:33.120 --> 58:39.760
When he went to the moon in 1969 only the

58:39.760 --> 58:42.820
fourth man to walk on the moon.

58:43.640 --> 58:46.540
He took some tartan with him.

58:47.180 --> 58:51.460
Scots like to go to new places.

58:53.120 --> 58:58.840
Who is the most famous Scot in the world today?

58:59.840 --> 59:05.700
To many people it is the film star Sean Connery

59:05.700 --> 59:07.600
born 1930.

59:09.280 --> 59:15.200
Sean Connery did a lot of different jobs before he

59:15.200 --> 59:18.440
began working in television and cinema.

59:19.440 --> 59:26.780
Then in 1962 he was James Bond in the first

59:26.780 --> 59:30.240
James Bond film Doctor No.

59:31.220 --> 59:35.220
After this he was famous everywhere.

59:36.660 --> 59:42.920
He made six more James Bond films and made many

59:42.920 --> 59:44.980
other films after that.

59:45.960 --> 59:54.300
To many people his best film is The Untouchables 1987.

59:55.480 --> 01:00:02.360
Connery does not make films now and does not live

01:00:02.360 --> 01:00:06.880
in Scotland but he loves Scotland very

01:00:06.880 --> 01:00:11.380
much and does not want it to be part of

01:00:11.380 --> 01:00:12.420
the United Kingdom.

01:00:26.760 --> 01:00:34.060
Chapter 11 Scotland Today and Tomorrow

01:00:34.060 --> 01:00:44.700
The story of Scotland is interesting and sometimes exciting but

01:00:44.700 --> 01:00:48.040
it is not an easy story.

01:00:49.240 --> 01:00:56.200
Some Scots like Sean Connery want Scotland to be just

01:00:56.200 --> 01:01:00.840
Scotland and not part of the United

01:01:00.840 --> 01:01:08.680
Kingdom. Scotland is still a country of rich and poor.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:17.380
The past is important but many Scots also want to

01:01:17.380 --> 01:01:21.720
think about Scotland today and tomorrow.

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:30.600
The Scots in the USA, Australia, Canada and New Zealand

01:01:30.600 --> 01:01:35.060
love the old things, the music,

01:01:36.080 --> 01:01:42.740
the dancing, the tartans but many of the Scots in

01:01:42.740 --> 01:01:47.760
Scotland want their country to look to

01:01:47.760 --> 01:01:54.860
the future, not the past. Scotland they say can be

01:01:54.860 --> 01:02:00.120
like Norway, a country with 5 million

01:02:00.340 --> 01:02:07.240
people and with a lot of money from oil. Scotland

01:02:07.240 --> 01:02:11.440
has money from oil, fish farming,

01:02:12.220 --> 01:02:21.640
visits from tourists, banks, computers and many other businesses and

01:02:21.640 --> 01:02:24.340
there is new life

01:02:24.340 --> 01:02:32.880
here, new business, new cinema, new music. Things are changing

01:02:32.880 --> 01:02:34.140
in Scotland.

01:02:35.260 --> 01:02:42.780
Today there is a Scottish Parliament in Edinburgh. It is

01:02:42.780 --> 01:02:44.700
in an interesting new building

01:02:44.700 --> 01:02:51.340
on the Royal Mile. People from every town and city

01:02:51.340 --> 01:02:55.580
in Scotland come here to talk about

01:02:55.580 --> 01:03:02.720
their country. Some Scots want Scotland to speak for itself

01:03:02.720 --> 01:03:06.280
in Europe and in the world.

01:03:08.100 --> 01:03:15.360
What is in the future for Scotland? Nobody knows but

01:03:15.360 --> 01:03:20.320
it is always going to be a beautiful

01:03:20.320 --> 01:03:28.040
special place. Perhaps one day you can walk along the

01:03:28.040 --> 01:03:32.300
Royal Mile, climb the hills or travel

01:03:32.300 --> 01:03:36.240
to the islands and see it for yourself.

